SIMPLE: surrender
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Surrender
<hw>Sur*ren"der</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Surrendered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Surrendering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF.
<ets>surrendre</ets> to deliver; <ets>sur</ets> over + <ets>rendre</ets>
to render. See <er>Sur-</er>, and <er>Render</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To yield to the power of another; to give or deliver up possession
of (anything) upon compulsion or demand; <as>as, to <ex>surrender</ex>
one's person to an enemy or to an officer; to <ex>surrender</ex> a fort
or a ship</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To give up possession of; to yield; to resign;
<as>as, to <ex>surrender</ex> a right, privilege, or
advantage</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>surrender</qex> up that right which otherwise their
founders might have in them.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To yield to any influence, emotion, passion, or
power; -- used reflexively; <as>as, to <ex>surrender</ex> one's self to
grief, to despair, to indolence, or to sleep</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>To yield; to render or deliver up;
to give up; <as>as, a principal <ex>surrendered</ex> by his bail, a
fugitive from justice by a foreign state, or a particular estate by the
tenant thereof to him in remainder or reversion</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Surrender</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Surrender
<hw>Sur*ren"der</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To give up one's self into
the power of another; to yield; <as>as, the enemy, seeing no way of
escape, <ex>surrendered</ex> at the first summons</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Surrender</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Surrender
<hw>Sur*ren"der</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of
surrendering; the act of yielding, or resigning one's person, or the
possession of something, into the power of another; <as>as, the
<ex>surrender</ex> of a castle to an enemy; the <ex>surrender</ex> of a
right</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That he may secure some liberty he makes a <qex>surrender</qex> in
trust of the whole of it.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The yielding of a
particular estate to him who has an immediate estate in remainder or
reversion.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The giving up of a principal into
lawful custody by his bail.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>The delivery up of
fugitives from justice by one government to another, as by a foreign
state. See <er>Extradition</er>.</def> <rj><au>Wharton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Insurance)</fld> <def>The voluntary cancellation of
the legal liability of the company by the insured and beneficiary for a
consideration (called the <col><b>surrender value</b></col>).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Surrenderee</ent>⟦br⟧
